04190nam a22006255i 9780271056623DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212008pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710566237 a10.1515/97802710566232doi  a(DE-B1597)583658  a(OCoLC)1262307415  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aPOL0420202bisacsh04a320.1/12221 aButton, Mark E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aContract, Culture, and Citizenship :bTransformative Liberalism from Hobbes to Rawls /cMark E. Button. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 "Where Justice Is Called a Virtue": Public Reason and Civic Formation in Thomas Hobbes -- t2 Compact Before Liberal Constructivism: The Divine Politics of John Locke -- t3 Governing Subjects and Breeding Citizens: Dilemmas of Public Reasoning and Public Judgment in Locke -- t4 Rousseau's Contractarian Republic: The Culture of Constitutional Self-Government -- t5 John Rawls, Public Reason, and Transformative Liberalism Today -- tConclusion: The Politics of Not Settling Down -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe idea of the social contract has typically been seen in political theory as legitimating the exercise of governmental power and creating the moral basis for political order. Mark Button wants to draw our attention to an equally crucial, but seldom emphasized, role for the social contract: its educative function in cultivating the habits and virtues that citizens need to fulfill the promises that the social contract represents. In this book, he retells the story of social contract theory as developed by some of its major proponents-Hobbes, Locke, Rousseau, and Rawls-highlighting this constructive feature of the theory in order to show that not only do citizens make the social contract, but the social contract also makes citizens. Button's interest in recovering this theme from past political theory is not merely historical, however. He means to resurrect our concern for it so that we can better understand the political-institutional and cultural-ethical conditions necessary for balancing individual freedom and common citizenship in our modern world of moral pluralism. Drawing on the history of public reason, Button shows how political justification continues to depend upon an ethics of character formation and why this matters for citizens today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Conservatism & Liberalism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271056623zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271056623423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271056623.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK